<subsection xml:id="subsection-relating-different-ratios-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Relating different ratios in real life</title>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Instructions</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Mr Kamboi, a Grade <m>9</m> teacher, organized for a short distance race. The race had <m>5</m> stations that is station <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, <m>D</m> and <m>E</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The distance between the stations is as follows:
            </p>
            <tabular top="medium">
                <row left="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" >Station</cell>
                    <cell right="medium">Position in (m)</cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium">A</cell>
                    <cell right="medium">0</cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium">B</cell>
                    <cell right="medium">20</cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium">C</cell>
                    <cell right="medium">40</cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium">D</cell>
                    <cell right="medium">80</cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium">E</cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium">160</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use the information in the table to make a sketch showing the stations and the distances between them.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If the distance between the stations is in continued proportion, find the distance between station <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>, <m>C</m> and <m>D</m>, and <m>D</m> and <m>E</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify any proportional relationships between the distance <m>AB</m> and <m>CD</m> and the distance <m>BC</m> and <m>DE</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Work out the ratio of <m>AB:BC</m> and <m>CD:DE</m> in simplest form.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with your fellow learners.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <definition xml:id="def-continued-proportion">
        <statement>
            <p>
               
              If <m>4</m> numbers, <m>a, b, c</m> and <m>d</m> are in continued proportion, then:
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>\frac{a}{b} = \frac{b}{c} = \frac{c}{d}</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\quad\quad</m>Since 
                <me>\frac{a}{b} = \frac{b}{c},</me> <m>\quad\quad</m>then <me> b^2 = ac</me>
            </p>
            <p>
               <m>\quad\quad</m>Therefore,  
            </p> 
            <p>
                <me>b = \pm \sqrt{ac} </me>
            </p>
            
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <alert>Key Takeaway</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
       <m>\bullet</m> When numbers are in continued proportion, they form a geometric progression because each term is obtained by multiplying the previous term by the same common ratio.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\bullet</m> For example, consider the numbers <m>3, 6, 12, 24</m>.  
        Here, each number is equal to the previous number multiplied by <m>2</m>.  
        Since the common ratio is <m>2</m>, the four numbers are said to be in continued proportion.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\bullet</m> In real life, ratios help us compare quantities. For example, if James takes <m>5</m> minutes to solve a math problem and Esther takes <m>4</m> minutes for the same task, we can compare their times using the ratio <m>5:4</m>.  
        Ratios like this allow us to see how one quantity relates to another in everyday situations.
   </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If the ratio of the ages of John and Mary is <m>3:4</m>, and the ratio of their ages in <m>5</m> years will be <m>4:5</m>, what are their current ages?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let John's current age be <m>3x</m> and Mary's current age be <m>4x</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                In <m>5</m> years, their ages will be <m>3x + 5</m> and <m>4x + 5</m> respectively.
            </p>
            <p>
                Since the ratio of their ages at that time is given as <m>4:5</m>, we can write:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><mrow>\frac{3x + 5}{4x + 5} =\amp \frac{4}{5}</mrow></md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Cross-multiplying:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><mrow>5(3x + 5) =\amp 4(4x + 5)</mrow></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Expanding both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><mrow>15x + 25 =\amp 16x + 20</mrow></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplifying gives:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md><mrow>x =\amp 5</mrow></md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substituting back:
            </p>
            <p>
                John's current age = <md><mrow>3 \times 5 =\amp 15</mrow></md> years.
            </p>
            <p>
                Mary's current age = <md><mrow>4 \times 5 =\amp 20</mrow></md> years.
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, John is <m>15</m> years old and Mary is <m>20</m> years old.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Given that the ratio <m>x:y=2:3</m>, find the ratio <m>(5x - 2y):(x+y)</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
            Since <m>x:y = 2:3</m>, we can let:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x =\amp 2k</mrow>
                    <mrow>y =\amp 3k</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substituting into <m>(5x - 2y):(x+y)</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>5x - 2y =\amp 5(2k) - 2(3k)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 10k - 6k </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 4k</mrow>
                    <mrow>x + y =\amp 2k + 3k</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 5k </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                <mrow>(5x - 2y):(x+y) =\amp 4k:5k</mrow>
            </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplify the ratio by cancelling <m>k</m> (where <m>k â‰  0</m>):
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                <mrow>4:5</mrow>
            </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the ratio <m>(5x-2y):(x+y)</m> simplifies to <m>4:5</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>22, X</m> and <m>88</m> are in continued proportion, find the value of <m>X</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                If <m>22, X</m> and <m>88</m> are in continued proportion, then we can express this relationship as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{22}{X} =\amp \frac{X}{88}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Cross-multiplying gives us:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>22 \times 88 =\amp X^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplifying this, we have:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>1936 =\amp X^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Hence, <m>X = \sqrt{1936}</m> 
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>= 44 </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>    